   <body>
      <context>
         <hazardstatement type="danger">
            <messagepanel>
               <typeofhazard>hazard of electric shock, explosion, or arc flash</typeofhazard>
               <howtoavoid>
                  <sl>
                     <sli>Electrical equipment must be installed, operated, serviced, and
maintained only by qualified personnel.</sli>
                     <sli>Apply appropriate personal protective equipment (PPE) and follow
safe electrical work practices.</sli>
                     <sli>Disconnection devices for AC and DC must be provided by others,
be readily accessible, and the function of the disconnect device marked
for its function.</sli>
                     <sli>Turn off all power supplying the UPS system before working on
or inside the equipment.</sli>
                     <sli>Before working on the UPS system, check for hazardous voltage
between all terminals including the protective earth.</sli>
                     <sli>The UPS contains an internal energy source. Hazardous voltage
can be present even when disconnected from the mains supply. Before
installing or servicing the UPS system, ensure that the units are
OFF and that mains and batteries are disconnected. Wait five minutes
before opening the UPS to allow the capacitors to discharge.</sli>
                     <sli>The UPS must be properly earthed/grounded and due to a high leakage
current, the earthing/grounding conductor must be connected first.</sli>
                  </sl>
               </howtoavoid>
            </messagepanel>
         </hazardstatement>
         <note>This procedure shows the 80
kVA UPS but the procedure is identical for all UPS systems.</note>
      </context>
      <ol>
         <li>
            <p>Loosen the two nuts and remove the cover in the right side.</p>
            <stepxmp>
               <fig>
                  <image href="../Images/img_80_kva_replace_power_module_remove_cover_in_right_side_0000101752.png"
                         scalefit="yes"
                         placement="inline"/>
               </fig>
            </stepxmp>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Loosen the two nuts and slide out the fan module in front
of the power module as long as the cables allow.</p>
            <stepxmp>
               <fig>
                  <image href="../Images/img_80_kva_replace_power_module_remove_fan_module_0000101751.png"
                         scalefit="yes"
                         placement="inline"/>
               </fig>
            </stepxmp>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Note the location of the cables connected to the fan module
and disconnect the cables.</p>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Move the fan module completely out of the UPS cabinet.</p>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Loosen the two screws and the two nuts of each plate and
remove the plates.</p>
            <stepxmp>
               <image href="../Images/img_80_kva_replace-0p4916_remove1_0000104210.png"
                      scalefit="yes"
                      placement="inline"/>
            </stepxmp>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Slide out the power modules. Start with the upper power
module.</p>
            <stepxmp>
               <fig>
                  <image href="../Images/img_80_kva_replace_capacity_board_0p4916_slide_out_both_pms_0000104209.png"
                         scalefit="yes"
                         placement="inline"/>
               </fig>
            </stepxmp>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Loosen the four screws of each capacitor board.</p>
            <stepxmp>
               <fig>
                  <image href="../Images/img_80_kva_replace_capacity_board_0p4916_loosen_screws_0000102153.png"
                         scalefit="yes"
                         scope="local"
                         placement="inline"/>
               </fig>
            </stepxmp>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Note the location of cables connected to the two capacitor
boards and disconnect the cables.</p>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Lift the two capacitor board assemblies up and out of the
cabinet.</p>
            <stepxmp>
               <fig>
                  <image href="../Images/img_80_kva_replace_capacity_board_0p4916_slide_boards_up_and_out_0000102151.png"
                         scalefit="yes"
                         scope="local"
                         placement="inline"/>
               </fig>
            </stepxmp>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Remove the indicated screws.</p>
            <stepxmp>
               <fig>
                  <image href="../Images/img_80_kva_replace_the_power_connection_board_0j-0p2552_remove_indicated_screws_0000102330.png"
                         scalefit="yes"
                         placement="inline"/>
               </fig>
            </stepxmp>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Remove the indicated nuts and busbars.</p>
            <stepxmp>
               <fig>
                  <image href="../Images/img_80_kva_replace_the_power_connection_board_0j-0p2552_remove_screws_with_cutout_0000102329.png"
                         scalefit="yes"
                         placement="inline"/>
               </fig>
            </stepxmp>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Note the location of the cables connected to the power
connection board and disconnect the cables.</p>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Loosen the screws and lift the power connection board assembly
up and out of the cabinet.</p>
            <stepxmp>
               <fig>
                  <image href="../Images/img_80_kva_replace_the_power_connection_board_0j-0p2552_remove_board_with_cutout_0000102328.png"
                         scalefit="yes"
                         scope="local"
                         placement="inline"/>
               </fig>
            </stepxmp>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>On the new replacement power connection board assembly:</p>
            <ol>
               <li>
                  <p>For 380–415 V range systems: Cut the marked bridges.</p>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <p>For 220–240 V range systems: Cut the marked bridges.</p>
                  <stepxmp>
                     <fig expanse="page">
                        <title>0P2552 Power Connection Board Assembly</title>
                        <image href="../Images/0p2552_with_callouts_0000160528.svg" placement="inline"/>
                     </fig>
                  </stepxmp>
               </li>
            </ol>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Reverse the procedure for installation of the replacement
power connection board assembly.</p>
         </li>
      </ol>
